source.Name: Total population
source.Summary: Population: Total population and distribution by age and sex estimated to be consistent with the population by age and sex of the (a) 2005, 2017 censuses; (b) adjusted for under/over count; (c) adjusted for age heaping; (d) adjusted for under enumeration of children under age 15; (e) 1994 NHS survey estimates; (f) official estimates through 2023; (g) only total population for 1969 Census; and with estimates of the subsequent trends in fertility, mortality and international migration. In addition, the 2010 MICS survey estimates have been considered.

source.Name: Total fertility rate
source.Summary: Fertility: Total fertility rate and age pattern of fertility based on: (a) official estimates of age-specific fertility rates through 2005; (b) registered births classified by age of mother and the underlying female population by age through 2021; (c) birth-histories data from the 2012 NHS; (d) births in the household in the preceding 12 (or 24) months classified by age of mother from the 2007, 2012 LSS and 2010 MICS and 2017 Census; (e) indirect estimates obtained from the application of the reverse survival method to the 2005, 2017 censuses and 2010 MICS. In addition, the (a) births in the household in the preceding 12 (or 24) months classified by age of mother from the 2000 NHS and 2005 Census; (b) adjusted fertility using synthetic relational Gompertz model with data on children ever born and births in the preceding 12 (or 24/36) months, both classified by age of mother, from the 2005 Census; (c) indirect estimates obtained from the application of the reverse survival method to the 1958-2011 Education Stats and 1994 NHS; (d) indirect estimates obtained from the application of the own-children method of fertility estimation to the 2010 MICS; (e) cohort-completed fertility backdated by the mean age of childbearing from the 2005 Census and 2010 MICS have been considered.

source.Name: Life expectancy at birth
source.Summary: Overall Mortality: Life expectancy at birth and age pattern of mortality based on: (a) registered deaths by age and sex available through 2021; (b) In the absence of statistics indicative of mortality levels and trends, mortality was assumed to have levels similar to those estimated for neighbouring countries with similar socio-economic conditions; (c) estimates of under-five mortality (5q0) by assuming that the age pattern of mortality conforms to the CD West model life tables.

source.Name: Age Mortality
source.Summary: Adult and Old Age Mortality: Estimates derived from: (a) recent household deaths data by age and sex from the 2005 Census; (b) recent household deaths adjusted at adult ages for underregistration using death distribution methods; (c) estimates of under-five, adult and old age mortality. In addition, the (a) siblings deaths from the 2010 MICS; (b) maternal orphanhood from the 2010 MICS; (c) paternal orphanhood from the 2010 MICS; (d) indirect estimates of male adult mortality based on female widowhood data from the 2005, 2017 censuses and 2010 MICS; (e) indirect estimates of female adult mortality based on male widowhood data from the 2005, 2017 censuses and 2010 MICS; (f) intercensal survivorship from successive census age distributions have been considered.

source.Name: Infant/child mortality
source.Summary: Child Mortality: Under-five mortality based on: (a) direct estimates from births and deaths under-five calculated from full birth histories data from the 1984 DSS and 2000, 2012 NHS; (b) indirect estimates from data on children ever born and surviving from the 1984 DSS and 2005 Census and 2010 MICS; (c) recent household deaths from the 1994 NHS and 2005 Census; (d) International estimates used up to 2021. In addition, the (a) registered infant and child deaths through 2021; (b) recent household deaths from the 2017 Census have been considered.

source.Name: International migration
source.Summary: Migration: International migration based on: (a) information on foreign-born populations from censuses and registers from major countries of destination; (b) estimates derived as the differences between overall population growth and natural increase; (c) UNHCR statistics on the number of refugees in the main countries of asylum.
